data.value: It consists of three types of fibers: Protection, commissurals and association. Projection fibers are corticopetal and corticofugal fibers, joining the bark in both directions with the underlying centers. These fibers converge around the ribbed body and thalamus, forming the radiated crown. Commissural fibers unite the two hemispheres, forming the corpus callosum, the fornix and the previous white Commission. • The corpus callosum is shaped like an arc of cranio-caudal flattened circle, showing a body whose curved anterior extremity, called the knee, ends with a sharp portion, called the rostrum, which lengthens with the terminal blade. The more voluminous posterior extremity is called the splenium. The upper face of the corpus callosum is wrapped by a blade of gray substance - indusium griseum or supracalosal gir. The upper face of the corpus callosum comes in relation to the brain’s hump and the lower sagittal venous sinus. The fibers of the corpus callosum radiate into the white matter of the cerebral hemispheres, forming the radiation of the corpus callosum. The fibers that radiate to the knee form minor forceps that join the medial faces of the frontal lobes. The fibers at the level of the splenic make up, in the occipital lobe, major forceps. • Fornix (brain trine) is located under the corpus callosum. At the center, the body of the fornix is shown. Previously, the body divides into the two columns that head toward the two mamilar bodies, and posterior the body heads toward the hippocampus, a formation belonging to the limbic system. • The previous white commissure passes the columns of the fomix and splits into the anterior region of the temporal lobe.

In the fifth layer of motor area 4 there are also giant pyramidal neurones (Betz) (120 to 150 microns), which are in the number of about 30000. • Granular neurones are polygonal in shape and sizes ranging from 4 to 8 microns. Granular neurones have numerous dendrites that go in all directions. Their Axon is short and branches in the vicinity of the neural body. Granular neurones are found in all layers of the crust, but are more numerous in layers 2 and 4. • Fusiform neurones are found in the deep layers of the crust. From both poles of the fusiform neurones a dendrite (one ascending, the other descending) leaves. The ascending dendritis ascends to the superficial layers, and the descending one descends to the deep layers. From the deep pole of the fusiform neurones leaves the axon that can leave the bark, forming association and commissural fibers. • Horizontal Cajal cells are found only in the surface layer of the bark. Their Axon is horizontal and connects with the dendrites of pyramidal cells. • Martinotic cells are found in layers 3, 5, 6 of the crust. They have an ascending axon that reaches the surface layer of the crust. Fibers are also found in the brain’s crust, some of which are horizontal, others vertical.

data.value: They are an important nucleus of the extrapyramidal system and are located between the tala-mus and the bark of the island’s lobe. Striated bodies are represented by the caudate nucleus and the lentiform nucleus. The caudate nucleus is comma-shaped, surrounds the thalamus, and features a bulky head, which previously exceeds the thalamus, a body and a tail that reaches the temporal lobe. The lentiform nucleus, located laterally by the caudate nucleus, is triangular in shape on the section and features a darker side part called putamen and a lighter medial part called globus pallidus. The putment, along with the caudate nucleus, forms the neostriate, while globus pallidus forms the paleostriate. On the side of the lentiform nucleus is the claustrum, a blade of gray substance whose function is not specified. Between the thalamus and the caudate nucleus, on the one hand, and the lentiform nucleus, on the other hand, the internal white capsule is displayed. Between the lentiform nucleus and the claustrum is the external white capsule, and between the claustrum and the lobe of the island is the extreme white capsule. Neostriate receives fiber from the bark, the thalamus, and the black substance, sending fiber to the thalamus, bark, black substance, and globus pallidus. Paleostriate receives fiber from the bark, neostriate, thalamus, subthalamus and black substance.
